<subSubSection id="B08F70EE6EEF19EF14D38CB8928BF486" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="ecological notes">
<paragraph id="BD488CBD3F2610812CC095244A6C8828" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F0265505CC607A951706F17ADA68FA00" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
All four specimens were collected during the day, beneath flowerpots, leaf litter substrates or other surface material. Their reduced limbs are folded alongside body during rapid locomotion (
<bibRefCitation id="3A145D9C8DFD0E551CBDC4395687E737" author="Das, I" journalOrPublisher="New Holland Publishers, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" refId="B6" refString="Das, I, 2010. A field guide to the reptiles of South-East Asia. New Holland Publishers, London" title="A field guide to the reptiles of South-East Asia." year="2010">Das 2010</bibRefCitation>
), whereas they are unfolded when slowly crawling.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BA6CA02C9C5AD721D97CF0A35327F17D" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
Diet and reproductive habits remain poorly known. Nevertheless, a large number of ants were observed where the specimens were collected, and probably served as their main food source, which was similar to the habitats as inferred from 
<bibRefCitation id="51D99B142B4F1D886D8805CAB71839FF" author="Das, I" journalOrPublisher="New Holland Publishers, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" refId="B6" refString="Das, I, 2010. A field guide to the reptiles of South-East Asia. New Holland Publishers, London" title="A field guide to the reptiles of South-East Asia." year="2010">Das (2010</bibRefCitation>
: 83, plate 33). 
<bibRefCitation id="D2BB87BCA1710836833ABD2843B9224A" author="Smith, M" journalOrPublisher="Taylor And Francis, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" refId="B20" refString="Smith, M, 1935. The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. II. Sauria. Taylor And Francis, London" title="The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. II. Sauria." year="1935">Smith (1935)</bibRefCitation>
reported the reproductive habits in stating &quot;A female kept by me in Bangkok laid three eggs on May 27th measuring 9 by 5 mm. in size. The young were born on June 28th and measured 48 mm. in total length, the head and body measuring 26 mm&quot;.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
